article.description: LaToya Thomas had 18 points and eight rebounds Sunday, helping the Cleveland Rockers defeat the Detroit Shock 66-59 to even the first-round playoff at one game each.
article.headline: Rockers get road win to even series
article.linkText: Thomas helps Rockers force deciding game
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Cleveland Rockers knew their
season depended on doing something they hadn't done all year.

Beat the Detroit Shock.

The Rockers did just that, getting 16 points and eight rebounds
from rookie LaToya Thomas on Sunday to stave off elimination with a
66-59 victory and force Game 3 in the first-round playoff.

The Shock swept the four regular-season games from the Rockers,
then opened the best-of-three series with a 76-74 win in Cleveland.
Three of Detroit's five wins came by three points or less.

"We didn't let ourselves get frustrated by Detroit," Thomas
said. "I know that teams can let that happen, but we didn't. We
just came out and played a good game."

Game 3 is Tuesday night at the Palace, with the winner facing
Connecticut in the Eastern Conference finals.

"We played a 34-game regular season and finished with the best
record strictly for this reason," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer
said. "We wanted to make sure a deciding game will be on our
court."

Cleveland lost reserve guard Merlakia Jones to a mild concussion
in the first half after her head banged into Kedra Holland-Corn's
hip. Her status for Game 3 is unclear.

Betty Lennox had 14 points for Cleveland while Penny Taylor
added 12 and Chasity Melvin scored 10.

Swin Cash led Detroit with 17 points, while Ruth Riley had 14
and Cheryl Ford had nine points and 11 rebounds. The Shock shot 29
percent, their worst performance of the season.

"I was really surprised at the way it happened," Cash said.
"Usually, we might have one or two people who might be off, but
someone else will get it going. Today, though, we never found
anyone with the hot hand."

Cleveland took a 23-13 lead as Detroit missed 15 of its first 18
shots, and was still ahead 39-28 edge at halftime. Detroit shot 25
percent for the half.

The Rockers went up 45-30, early in the second half. Cash had
four points in an 11-3 run that drew Detroit to 48-41 with 11:57 to
go, then the rally stalled. The Shock were down 55-50 with six
minutes to play, but Cleveland scored the next seven points.

"You have to earn wins in this league, and that's what we
haven't done against Detroit," Rockers coach Dan Hughes said.
"You can't just put yourself in a position to win, you have to
also finish it off. We finally did that against them."

Laimbeer received the league's coach of the year award before
the game while Ford was honored as rookie of the year.
